headline_main: Here’s What Happened in N.F.L. Week 7

abstract: Representative Frederica S. Wilson said John F. Kelly, the president’s chief of staff, lied by suggesting she had taken credit for obtaining funding for a federal building in Miami.
snippet: Representative Frederica S. Wilson said John F. Kelly, the president’s chief of staff, lied by suggesting she had taken credit for obtaining funding for a federal building in Miami.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Video of a 2015 speech delivered by Representative Frederica S. Wilson revealed Friday that John F. Kelly, the White House chief of staff, misrepresented her remarks when he accused her of bragging about securing $20 million for a South Florida F.B.I. building and twisting President Barack Obama’s arm.

abstract: His exhibition at Parasol unit foundation for contemporary art in London includes more than 30 sculptures and works on paper spanning about four decades.
snippet: His exhibition at Parasol unit foundation for contemporary art in London includes more than 30 sculptures and works on paper spanning about four decades.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — “Shackled” is a black iron sculpture by the artist Martin Puryear. The metal hoop at the top is reminiscent of the cuffs once used aboard slave ships. Yet when viewed for more than a few seconds, the artwork sheds its political overtones and appears more and more as a sophisticated work of abstraction with delicate, animallike contours.

abstract: Criticized for earlier overlooking the scandal, “Saturday Night Live” addressed it this weekend, with varying degrees of comfort and effectiveness.
snippet: Criticized for earlier overlooking the scandal, “Saturday Night Live” addressed it this weekend, with varying degrees of comfort and effectiveness.
lead_paragraph: After being criticized last weekend for not tackling Harvey Weinstein and the multiple accusations of sexual harassment and assault that he faces, “Saturday Night Live” addressed the subject in a comedy sketch and on “Weekend Update,” with varying degrees of comfort and effectiveness.

abstract: Two week after the league stared down President Trump, Roger Goodell sent a letter to owners saying “we believe that everyone should stand for the national anthem.”
snippet: Two week after the league stared down President Trump, Roger Goodell sent a letter to owners saying “we believe that everyone should stand for the national anthem.”
lead_paragraph: By appearances anyway, the N.F.L. was one big family two weeks ago. After President Trump urged owners to fire players who did not stand for the national anthem, everyone from Commissioner Roger Goodell to the 32 team owners to the players and coaches locked arms, in many cases literally, in defiance and unity.

abstract: Joseph Lombardo, the head of the Las Vegas police, must grapple with finding the motive for a horrific mass shooting while keeping the public calm and reporters at bay.
snippet: Joseph Lombardo, the head of the Las Vegas police, must grapple with finding the motive for a horrific mass shooting while keeping the public calm and reporters at bay.
lead_paragraph: LAS VEGAS — In nearly 30 years with the Las Vegas police, Joseph Lombardo has helped defuse an armed standoff between federal agents and local ranchers, struggled to contain a spike in homicides and defended his officers against accusations of using excessive force against a professional football player.

abstract: Thousands of people who had come from far away suddenly found themselves under fire.
snippet: Thousands of people who had come from far away suddenly found themselves under fire.
lead_paragraph: The weekend was perfect for an escape. It was Las Vegas, the poster city for getting away, and a dazzling lineup of entertainment beckoned, a three-day country music festival known as Route 91.
